== What to Do While Laboring at Home

The hours you spend laboring at home during early labor are not wasted time. They are an investment in the quality of your birth experience. Here's how to make the most of them.

=== Setting Up Your Environment

Before labor begins (ideally in the weeks leading up to your due date), prepare your home for laboring:

- *Bedroom:* Install a dimmer switch or have low-wattage lamps ready. Put fresh sheets on the bed. Have extra pillows available. Place a waterproof mattress pad under your sheets in case your water breaks.
- *Bathroom:* Clean the tub and shower. Have towels easily accessible. Consider a waterproof Bluetooth speaker for music.
- *Kitchen:* Stock easy-to-prepare foods and electrolyte drinks. Fill water bottles and put them in the refrigerator. Prepare ice in advance.
- *General:* Have your birth ball inflated and ready. Prepare a "labor station" with your phone charger, contraction timer app, heating pad, massage tools, lip balm, hair ties, and snacks.
- *Hospital bag:* Have it packed and by the door. Include your birth plan, insurance cards, phone charger, comfortable clothes, and anything else you'll want at the hospital.

=== Comfort Measures

*Movement and positioning:*
- Walking gently around your home or neighborhood (not power-walking)
- Swaying side-to-side with partner support
- Slow dancing together --- arms around your partner's neck, swaying to music
- Hands-and-knees position (excellent for back labor and helping a posterior baby rotate)
- Sitting on a birth ball, rocking hips in circles or figure-eights
- Leaning forward over a table, counter, or the back of a couch
- Lunging gently with one foot elevated on a stair or chair

*Water comfort:*
- Warm shower with water directed on your back or belly
- Full immersion in a tub (can reduce pain perception by approximately 25%)
- The deeper and warmer the water, the more effective the relief
- Consider waiting until active labor to use the tub for maximum benefit

*Other relief:*
- Heating pad or rice sock on lower back
- Slow, deep breathing --- in through the nose, out through the mouth
- Low moaning or vocalization (releases tension; keep vocalizations low-pitched rather than high-pitched)
- Distraction with movies, music, podcasts, or audiobooks during early labor
- Counter-pressure: partner pressing firmly on the sacrum (lower back) during contractions

=== Partner's Role at Home

Research is clear: continuous presence and support from a trained partner reduces pain perception, lowers anxiety, reduces need for pain medication, and increases satisfaction with birth.#citation[9]

*During contractions:*
- Stay close and in physical contact if she wants it
- Offer firm pressure on lower back or sacrum
- Provide grounding words: "You're doing great," "Breathe with me," "One contraction at a time"
- Move with her if she's swaying or rocking
- Remind her to breathe slowly if she's holding her breath or breathing rapidly
- Stay calm --- your anxiety directly increases hers through mirror neurons and hormonal feedback

*Between contractions:*
- Offer water, electrolyte drinks, and food
- Help her change positions every 30 to 60 minutes
- Provide emotional reassurance
- Be fully present --- do not leave to check your phone, scroll social media, or call relatives
- Help maintain the environment --- dim lights, quiet music if desired, comfortable temperature

=== Eating, Drinking, and Rest

Labor uses enormous energy. Dehydration and low blood sugar lead to fatigue, which often prompts hospital transfer or increases the perceived need for interventions.

*What to eat:*
- Easy-to-digest foods: yogurt, eggs, toast with honey, smoothies, broth, fruit, oatmeal
- Follow your appetite --- it will naturally decrease as labor intensifies
- Small, frequent snacks are better than large meals
- Avoid heavy, greasy, or highly acidic foods

*What to drink:*
- Water alone is not sufficient --- you need electrolytes and calories
- Electrolyte drinks: coconut water, sports drinks, bone broth
- Juice for natural sugar and quick energy
- Herbal tea (raspberry leaf tea has a long traditional association with labor, though evidence is mixed)
- Aim for at least a few sips between every contraction

*Rest:*
- Alternate periods of activity with rest
- Lie down between contractions if tired, especially during nighttime labor
- Don't labor intensely the entire time --- rest is not laziness, it is strategy
- If early labor begins at night, prioritize sleep above all else

=== When to Call Your Provider

Even if you're planning to labor at home, you should call your provider (OB, midwife, or the hospital's labor and delivery line) to let them know labor has started. Most providers want a heads-up call when:

- You believe you are in early labor (regular contractions have begun)
- Your water breaks (even if contractions haven't started)
- You have any concerns or questions
- You're getting ready to head to the hospital

When you call, be prepared to share:
- How far apart your contractions are and how long they last
- Whether your water has broken, and if so, the color and odor of the fluid
- Whether the baby is moving normally
- Any other symptoms (bleeding, fever, headache, etc.)
- Your emotional state --- are you still chatty, or have you become quiet and focused?

Your provider can help you assess whether it's time to come in or whether you should continue laboring at home. Don't hesitate to call --- this is exactly what they are there for.

=== The Departure Checklist

When you've decided it's time to go to the hospital, here's a quick mental checklist:

+ *Confirm the pattern:* Contractions are 3 minutes apart (or meeting your personalized guideline), lasting about 1 minute, for at least 1 hour.
+ *Check the emotional signpost:* She has shifted from excitement to seriousness. She is focused inward and cannot be distracted.
+ *Call your provider or the hospital:* Let them know you're coming. Share your contraction timing and any other relevant information.
+ *Grab the hospital bag.* It should already be packed and by the door.
+ *Make arrangements:* If you have other children, pets, or responsibilities, activate your pre-arranged plan now.
+ *Don't rush.* Drive safely. Put towels on the car seat in case her water breaks. Have her sit in a reclined position if that's comfortable, or lean forward against a pillow. She can continue her breathing techniques in the car.
+ *Bring snacks and drinks for the partner.* You may be at the hospital for many hours. You need to stay fueled too.

