== When to Go IMMEDIATELY

While early labor is best managed at home for low-risk pregnancies, certain situations require immediate hospital evaluation regardless of contraction timing. Go right away if you experience:

*Heavy bleeding:* Bright red bleeding soaking more than one pad per hour, large blood clots, or continuous bleeding (not just spotting or bloody show). Some bloody mucus discharge is normal; heavy red bleeding is not.

*Baby not moving:* Significantly decreased movement or no movement for more than 2 hours when you would normally feel activity. First, try drinking something cold and sweet, lying on your left side, and waiting 30 minutes. If you still don't feel normal movement, go to the hospital immediately.

*Fever:* Temperature of 100.4 degrees Fahrenheit (38 degrees Celsius) or higher, especially with chills. Fever during labor may indicate infection, particularly if your water has already broken.

*Severe headache or vision changes:* A persistent, severe headache that won't go away with rest and hydration, seeing spots or flashing lights, or difficulty seeing clearly. These can indicate preeclampsia, a serious blood pressure condition that requires immediate medical attention.

*Severe abdominal pain outside of contractions:* Sharp, severe, constant belly pain that is not a contraction --- pain that does not come and go but remains constant. This could indicate placental abruption (premature separation of the placenta from the uterine wall) and is a medical emergency.

*Chest pain or difficulty breathing:* Pain in your chest accompanied by shortness of breath or difficulty breathing.

*Foul-smelling vaginal fluid:* If your water breaks and the fluid smells bad, it may indicate infection and requires evaluation.

*Greenish or brownish fluid:* If your water breaks and the fluid is not clear or light yellow, it may contain meconium (baby's first stool) and requires evaluation. Light staining may not be urgent, but dark green or thick fluid warrants immediate assessment.

*Cord prolapse:* If you feel something bulging in your vagina after your water breaks, or if you can see or feel the umbilical cord, call 911 immediately. Get onto your hands and knees with your chest on the floor and your hips elevated. Do not attempt to push the cord back in. This position uses gravity to keep the baby's weight off the cord.

*Sudden, severe pain that doesn't let up:* Normal labor contractions come in waves --- they build, peak, and release. If you experience sudden, severe, constant pain that does not come and go, this is not a contraction. It may indicate placental abruption or another emergency. Call 911 or have someone drive you to the hospital immediately.

*Trust your instincts:* If something feels wrong or different in a way you can't articulate, contact your provider. Maternal instinct is a real phenomenon, and experienced labor nurses will tell you that when a mother says "something is wrong," they take it seriously. It is always better to go in and have them say "everything's fine" than to wait at home wondering if something is wrong. You will never be judged for coming in to be checked. Your peace of mind matters, and so does your safety.

